<br>
I seem to underestimated the effort put forth into a multigroup raid.  I assumed that you just picked group, and then you go out and kill stuff.  This lack of strategy resulted in the death of lady Tylyn for which I am truly sorry.  I did not plan for more than one group and that was the problem.  <br>
<br>
My observations I take from this “raid” are:<br>
<br>
Plan the strategy BEFORE the raid begins.<br>
<br>
In the case of “my spot” in Burning Woods, adds are a given, and can be overwhelming.  When this is the case, one team pulls and battles while the other group/groups guard the area for adds.  Eventually this really worked well even though it was still unorganized, well, until we had 4 adds 2 of which were wurms.<br>
<br>
The raid leader must group people in accordance with their strengths and weaknesses.  <br>
<br>
Assure that you have a healer (no offense to Kronenburg, he was doing a fine job) in each group, targeting and healing is much easier that way.  <br>
<br>
<br>
Results:<br>
<br>
Well, we got some exp and had some fun, but no named Wurms showed and no “phat lewt”.  We got to try a few strategies, and I found out at least what doesn’t work.  I did a bit of hair pulling when peoples health got low, but Gallow did a great job keeping us all safe.  Thank you Gallow.<br>
<br>
<br>
Future:<br>
<br>
Now this is an open forum to discuss options for next time.  I would be glad to hear any recommendations on what went right and what went wrong, and how to fix it on the next raid.  I would love to try another multigroup in BW or anywhere else to get better at raid organization.  Maybe we can pull the giant fort or try the spot again as Harm still needs the wurm guts and I need some burning embers.<br>
<br>
THANK YOU ALL FOR COMING!!!  <br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
<br>
Jonan<br>
